<Content>Palace at a Price We wanted to stay somewhere nice for our 20th wedding anniversary weekendin September 2006 and I always fancied the Westin Palace from when I stayed in Madrid on buisness trips.I booked through the Starwood website.The hotel is well and conveniently situated in central Madrid near to the Retiro park and the museum quarter. It is a grand old building, with fine appointments, although it is starting to show its years of use just a little. The entrance hall is very grand, and the concierge very efficient. Our check in was very efficient, with a friendly and helpful counter agent who upgraded our room when she heard we were on our anniversary visit. Our room was small ( even upgraded) but beautifully appointed. We were a little disappointed that the much vaunted  heavenly bed was only a double, not a queen or king size, but it was opulently covered and quite comfortable.The bathroom and shower room was exemplary - it is a pity that one has to pay for a five star hotel in order to get such lovely and enjoyable facilities. The view from the small window was of the Plaza de Las Cortes - a bustling traffic roundabout and the retiro park beyond.After a reminder from me, the staff bought up the sparkling wine and flowers I had pre-booked for my wife. The delay did not spoil our visit.A quick look at the minibar and room service menus caused us to laugh - a small jar of jelly candies at 鈧?.50, and a Mars Bar 鈧? for example !!I popped out to the VIPS store on the Plaza to stock up on such items for a tenth of the price instead !The restaurant is very grand - airy and charismatic under a glass dome,but sadly also cripplingly bad value. Fortunately Madrid is well provided with fantastic eateries and we found several lovely venues over our stay, where we experienced wonderful local cuisine and ambience for realistic prices.The gym on the top floor is very well stocked with equipment, which seems to never be used. We were surprised that this lovely hotel 