<Author>Shant
<Content>Virtually flawless The Palace (now a Westin) has always been in competition with the Ritz which is well placed across the road. It is part of a rivalry which is unmatched by hotels in other cities, and while both were established by King Alfonso XIII to provide a similar service, The Ritz has had the better of the latter part of the 20th Century. However, Westin's take over of The Palace has breathed new life into the rivalry.The Palace has been restored to it's former glory. The days when the shine had come off the hotel have long since been forgotten, and the hotel is a Mecca for celebrity spotting, though this is something that is not new to The Palace, having seen the likes of Picasso, Ava Gardner and Rite Heyworth pass through it's doors. This can be a slight drawback though; on a recent visit, when attempting to get to the entrance, we had to fight through crowds of young girls held back by barricades, who were waiting to see their teen idols make an appearance from the hotels, however, beyond the doors lies an oasis of calm.On entering, the beautiful domed lounge awaits you. You can choose any descriptive term to depict the hotel: elegant, turn of the century grandeur, sumptuous. In it's own way, it is still understated, which adds to it's charm. Front desk staff can be rude, unresponsive and very dismissive. Concierge is acceptable, but not as good as many other Madrid hotels. They will not lead you off the beaten track and will advise you of places that are rather mainstream, well known and sometimes, touristy. They do not even attempt to be a little inventive, however, perhaps this caused problems in the past.The rest of the hotel staff are perfect. There is nothing you can flaw them on. Fast, efficient, knowledgeable, very professional. Rooms were perfect; a good size, nothing was overlooked and there were little touches everywhere which made the stay ever more pleasurable. By the time we were ready to leave, I really felt as though I had been well looked after. Dining at the hotel is superb. Try La Cupola. It is beyond excellent and is well worthy of the hotel it is within. The Westin is also in the heart of Madrid. Everything touristy is within a stone's throw of The Palace, and there are plentiful places to eat around the hotel. You can choose any dining experience, from fine dining to tapas. Sitting under the dome of the Westin's central atrium, you could just lose yourself completely....until the reality hits you that a drink in the atrium is the same cost as four drinks at the great bar next door, however, you stay here for luxury and exuberance, and if you stay here, you need to factor in these costs too.It is well worth the stay here. The extra Euros you spend staying at The Palace may make you shorten your stay in Madrid, but you will get far more out of a break there. It is well worth it. I will definitely go back there. 
